{
  "text": "where λ 0 , f , R * n , and G are variables of rain-fed farmlands before land use change, ∆S = −S ↓ × ∆α, where ∆α is the monthly albedo change between paddy fields and rain-fed farmlands; ∆G is the change in the monthly mean heat diffused into/out of the subsurface between paddy fields and rain-fed farmlands. Both ∆α and ∆G in Equation (5) are calculated based on the regional statistical mean values of rain-fed farmland and paddy fields. ∆ f is the change in the monthly mean energy redistribution factor, indicating the variation of f between paddy fields and rain-fed farmlands. As the energy redistribution factor of the Sanjiang Plain we calculated is a ten-year average value, which involves both properties of rain-fed farmland and paddy fields in the paddy field expansion areas, we used the regional statistical mean value of unchanged rain-fed farmland and unchanged paddy field pixels to indicate the change of the energy redistribution factor for paddy field expansion. Then the first, second, and third right hand terms in Equation (5) represent the contribution of the land surface temperature response from the albedo change (∆α), the change in heat conducted by the surface medium (∆G), and the change in energy redistribution factor (∆ f ), respectively [CITATION_1] .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "90710482"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "90710482": {
      "title": "Local Temperature Response to Land Cover and Management Change Driven by Non-Radiative Processes",
      "abstract": "Remote sensing and in situ observations show that non-radiative mechanisms dominate the local climatic response to land cover and land management changes in most regions of the globe for 8 of 9 common land cover and management perturbations."
    }
  }
}